Creating a **responsive grid layout using CSS Grid** is a powerful way to structure your web content. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you build a responsive grid layout using **CSS Grid**.

---

## ✅ 1. Basic HTML Structure

Start with a container that will hold your grid items.

```html
<div class="grid-container">
  <div class="grid-item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="grid-item">Item 2</div>
  <div class="grid-item">Item 3</div>
  <div class="grid-item">Item 4</div>
  <div class="grid-item">Item 5</div>
  <div class="grid-item">Item 6</div>
</div>
```

---

## ✅ 2. Basic CSS Grid Setup

Use `display: grid` on the container and define the number of columns.

```css
.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 16px;
  padding: 16px;
}
```

### Explanation:

- `display: grid`: Turns the container into a grid.
- `grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr))`:
  - `auto-fit`: Automatically adjusts the number of columns based on the container size.
  - `minmax(200px, 1fr)`: Each column is at least 200px wide and takes up equal space (1fr).
- `gap`: Adds space between grid items.
- `padding`: Adds space around the grid.

---

## ✅ 3. Responsive Grid with Media Queries

To make the grid responsive on different screen sizes, use media queries.

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .grid-container {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr; /* 1 column on small screens */
  }
}

@media (min-width: 769px) and (max-width: 1024px) {
  .grid-container {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); /* 2 columns on medium screens */
  }
}

